                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "\n                              <p>\n                                        <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>\n                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>\n                              </p>\n                              <p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                                        <placeName>London</placeName>\n                                        <date>4th January 5611</date>\n                              </p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(4)\">Most Esteemed Friend</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(7)\">I have read attentively your statement and<lb/>\n                                        communication to me of the <date>24th Iyar</date> from which\n                                        as well as from the course of our<lb/> correspondence I have\n                                        drawn in full and can well make out the character of such\n                                        individu<lb/>=als <add>הפושעים המורדים בך</add>\n                                        <persName>Brother Leeser</persName>! <add>דום לה' והתחולל\n                                                  לו</add> in the course of our correspondence you\n                                        had<lb/> occasion to remind me of the saying <add>לא לחכם\n                                                  הלך זרזיר וכ\"ו</add> on my reflecting thereon it\n                                        struck<lb/> me rather strange that such has been the case\n                                        throughout the proceedings for in that<lb/>\n                                        <hi rend=\"underline\">true</hi>\n                                        <persName>Lady Clarissa</persName> (whom I have never seen\n                                        since) of course you are well acquainted with<lb/> her\n                                                  <add>ספר יוחסין</add> Father, Brothers, brother in\n                                        law &amp;c Butchers <add>עסקם בבהמות</add> and for her having<lb/>\n                                        <del>having</del> taken such interest and under handed work\n                                        for a certain party she surely<lb/> must have had a scent\n                                                  <add>ריחא מלתא היא</add> that he is as well as\n                                        herself <add>מוחס</add> in the same way by father,<lb/>\n                                        grand father, great grand father &amp;c although butchers in\n                                        this country are closer to the<lb/> mark of <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">imitating</hi> a gentleman's\n                                        business, by their having a Desk to write upon, cheque<lb/>\n                                        book, banker, and after business hour attending at meetings\n                                        with a fine coat (of course<lb/> at that moment divested\n                                        from the <hi rend=\"underline\">blue apron</hi>) which is not\n                                        the case in <placeName>Leghorn</placeName> they are<lb/>\n                                        literally <add>שותפו של עמלק שפלים בתכלית השפלות</add> and\n                                        in no better sphere than the common drover, here;<lb/>\n                                        consequently this may in part answer the conduct of his\n                                        behaviour towards yourself &amp;<lb/> myself, for you know\n                                        well <add>זרוק חוטרא לאוירא אעיקרא קאי</add> when I say\n                                        myself I mean to say<lb/> that near his departure or during\n                                        the treatise of the affair he approached me closer<lb/> than\n                                        he ever did for 4 years he was here, appearing friendly, and\n                                        open'd his mind to me<lb/> of course as his countryman &amp;\n                                        superior, (but I held all this with suspicion) nevertheless\n                                        he<lb/> had the most kind behaviour &amp; hospitality from\n                                        one and all at my house; such has<lb/> been the <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">amiable</hi> &amp; <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">modest</hi> Divine that he has\n                                        never had the politeness I shall not<lb/> say write me a\n                                        letter, but compt. to me, or my family, and I was the only\n                                        one who accompanied<lb/> him 7 miles to see him off by the\n                                        Train; I can only attribute such behavior chiefly to\n                                        the<lb/> above reason, and than as I took no hints of what\n                                        he was coming so friendly after me, and<lb/> what he wished,\n                                        he expected that I should have shelter'd him under one of\n                                        the great men that<lb/>\n                                        <placeName>Leghorn</placeName> had <hi rend=\"underline\">once\n                                                  upon a time</hi> the poor <add>תלמיד</add>\n                                        <sic>beginer</sic> of the present day, was quite\n                                        mistaken,<lb/> I know him well also his full weight, the\n                                        first rudiments of the Bible <add>דקדוק</add> grammar a\n                                        little<lb/> it is &amp; <add>?</add> with the learned\n                                        Lecturer. I could not allow him in our official\n                                        certificate<lb/> but the truth and that only, as far as his\n                                        competency as Hazan. With regard to <persName>E</persName>:\n                                                  <persName>H</persName>:\n                                        <persName>L</persName>:<lb/> you could easily perceive the\n                                        truth of the <hi rend=\"underline\">amiable</hi>, the other\n                                        Two <sic>naturaly</sic> falls; <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                                                  >modest</hi> to be to the contrary<lb/>\n                                        <add>רשי ודיני אורח חיים it is &amp;</add>\n                                        <hi rend=\"underline\">learned</hi>, <del>after</del> a\n                                        learned man will easily find that out, what can such a\n                                        judge<lb/> signify, who knows not the least in our\n                                        literature <add>מאין לו מיחומו, מגודל חכמתו</add> he cannot\n                                        translate one verse</p>\n                              "
                  },
